  "explanation": [
    {
      "heading": "Commits are Snapshots",
      "body": "Every `git commit` creates a **snapshot** of your entire project at that moment, identified by a SHA hash.\n\nCommits form a **directed acyclic graph (DAG)** — each commit points to its parent(s). The history is the path from HEAD back to the first commit.",
      "appearsAtStep": 0
    },
    {
      "heading": "Branches are Just Pointers",
      "body": "A branch is nothing more than a **lightweight pointer** to a commit. Creating a branch is instant — it just creates a new file with a commit hash in it.\n\n`main`, `feature`, `hotfix` are all just labels. When you commit on a branch, the pointer advances.",
      "appearsAtStep": 2,
      "callout": "HEAD is a special pointer — it tells Git which branch (and therefore which commit) you're currently on."
    },
    {
      "heading": "Merge — Joining Histories",
      "body": "A **3-way merge** happens when the branches have diverged: Git finds the common ancestor commit and combines both sets of changes into a new **merge commit**.\n\nThe merge commit has two parents — both branch tips.",
      "appearsAtStep": 5
    },
    {
      "heading": "Fast-Forward Merge",
      "body": "If one branch is directly ahead of the other (no divergence), Git can **fast-forward** — just move the pointer forward. No merge commit needed.\n\nThis is the cleanest case: linear history, no extra nodes.",
      "appearsAtStep": 6
    },
    {
      "heading": "Rebase — Rewrite History",
      "body": "Instead of creating a merge commit, `git rebase` **replays** your branch's commits on top of the target branch, one by one.\n\nResult: a clean linear history. But note — rebased commits get **new SHA hashes**. Never rebase shared/public branches.",
      "appearsAtStep": 8,
      "callout": "Golden rule: never rebase a branch that others are working on — you rewrite the commits they've based their work on."
    },
    {
      "heading": "Cherry-Pick and Reset vs Revert",
      "body": "- **Cherry-pick**: copy a specific commit from one branch to another. Useful for backporting fixes.\n- **Reset --hard**: destructively move HEAD back — commits are lost (unless you have the SHA).\n- **Revert**: safe alternative — creates a *new* commit that undoes the changes. History is preserved. Use on shared branches.",
      "appearsAtStep": 10
    }
  ],

